The Alpaca instruction format structures training examples as three fields: instruction (the task description), input (optional additional context), and output (the expected response). During training, these are formatted as: '### Instruction:
{instruction}

### Input:
{input}

### Response:
{output}'. This format teaches the model to follow instructions by training on thousands of instruction-output pairs. The format was popularized by Stanford Alpaca, which fine-tuned LLaMA using GPT-4 generated instruction data.
